Germany, Year Zero
May 8 always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies committed all kinds of excesses.
It was difficult to procure food.
My father was directly transported from his prison to central Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from nothing - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
For what future?
“You must help,” my mother said to me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to some distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card of "victim of fascism," while others displayed an Iron Cross obtained for services rendered late to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It's practically incredible, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and above all accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Camps of concentration like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and detainees.
On the contrary, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was goodwill on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate “their” part of Germany.
But there are nevertheless lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy is undoubtedly more easily rooted in a context of economic recovery.
For this, it is first of all necessary to have initiative, from individuals who wish to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Which explains the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries, and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey with concern for the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past to move forward towards the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and political democracy, Germany faced its past, with much success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatized countries therefore lead to confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first novelty, then an attempt to assume the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005 is an occasion to look back on the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and thus filled with hope.
